11 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Regulation of teletypes -- purpose -- administrative messaging --
12 rulemaking. (1) The use of teletypes facilitates communication between jails and detention centers, serving as
13 a tool to assist with bonding defendants held in remote or distant detention locations when physical presence is
14 impractical. This system was established to address logistical challenges, such as large bond transmittals or
15 situations in which local surety bail bond agents are temporarily unavailable. However, teletypes may not be
16 misused as a substitute for maintaining a meaningful and sufficient local presence. This section governs the
17 permitted use of teletypes to ensure efficiency, prevent system abuse, and protect the operational integrity of
18 jails and detention centers.
19 (2) To manage communication system demands effectively, detention centers are authorized to
20 establish and implement their own reasonable limits on the number of teletypes consistent with constitutional
21 rights, operational capacity, and institutional needs.
22 (3) Surety bail bond insurance producer agencies advertising as statewide providers shall maintain
23 enough licensed surety bail bond agents geographically distributed to reasonably support their claimed service
24 area. The ratio must be at least one licensed surety bail bond agent for each geographic area as determined by
25 the attorney general to qualify as a statewide provider. The agencies shall register licensed surety bail bond
26 agents in assigned regions with the attorney general, and the attorney general shall review compliance with this
27 subsection during license applications and renewals. The license application for agencies may include a fee
28 that is commensurate with the costs of administering this section.
