7 NEW SECTION. Section 16. Out-of-jurisdiction warrants -- prohibition on own recognizance
8 release. (1) Justices of the peace or judicial officers outside the jurisdiction where a warrant was issued are
9 prohibited from granting an own recognizance or release for a defendant arrested on that warrant.
10 (2) Defendants arrested on an out-of-jurisdiction warrant shall remain in custody or post bond as
11 specified in the warrant until the jurisdictional court is notified and involved.
12 (3) A defendant arrested on an out-of-jurisdiction warrant must be brought before a justice of the
13 peace or a court in the county of arrest without unnecessary delay.
14 (a) At the hearing, the court or justice of the peace must:
15 (i) inform the defendant of the charges and conditions outlined in the warrant;
16 (ii) confirm the identity of the defendant as the individual named in the warrant; and
17 (iii) notify the defendant of their right to post bond as specified in the warrant or await transfer to
18 the jurisdictional court.
19 (b) This notification process does not grant the justice of the peace or court in the arresting county
20 the authority to alter or override the conditions of release set by the issuing jurisdiction.
21 (4) A defendant arrested in a separate jurisdiction may post the bond amount specified in the
22 warrant without requiring an additional hearing. The arresting jurisdiction shall:
23 (a) accept the bond amount specified in the warrant; and
24 (b) notify the court of jurisdiction immediately on receipt of the bond payment and forward all
25 related documentation.
26 (5) The arresting county or jurisdiction shall notify the court of jurisdiction immediately on the
27 defendant's arrest or any bond posting. The notification must include details of the defendant's arrest, charges,
28 and bond payment to ensure the jurisdictional court can confirm the conditions of the release.
